ame forms, whereas in America all three forms of the name are approximately equally common.  See also  Alun ."]},{"name":"Albert","meanings":["From an Old French name, <i>Albert</i>, of Germanic (Frankish) origin, derived from <i>adal</i> ‘noble’ + <i>berht</i> ‘bright, famous’. This was adopted by the Normans and introduced by them to England, displacing the Old English form <i>Æþelbeorht</i>. The name is popular in a variety of forms in Western Europe, and has been traditional in a number of European princely families. It was out of favour in England for centuries, however, and the revival of its popularity in the 19th century was largely in honour of  Queen Victoria's  consort,  Prince Albert of Saxe-Coburg-Gotha ."]}]},{"name":"Llywarch","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Traditional, now only occasionally used: compound of the god's name <i>Lugu-</i> (  see  Lleu  ) + Old Celtic <i>marcos</i> ‘horse’."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"Mrs Cadafael Ynfyd ap Llywarch was born about 1100, in Wales. She had at least 1 son with Cadafael Ynfyd ap Llywarch."},"et":{"about 1100–":"umbes 1100–Surnud","1100–Male":"1100–Surnud","1130–Male":"1130–Surnud","1100–Female":"1100–Surnud","1100":"1100","1130":"1130","about 1100":"umbes 1100","Wales":"Wales"},"fi":{"about 1100–":"noin 1100–Kuollut","1100–Male":"1100–Kuollut","1130–Male":"1130–Kuollut","1100–Female":"1100–Kuollut","1100":"1100","1130":"1130","about 1100":"noin 1100","Wales":"Wales"},"fr":{"about 1100–":"environ 1100–Décédée","1100–Male":"1100–Décédé","1130–Male":"1130–Décédé","1100–Female":"1100–Décédée","1100":"1100","1130":"1130","about 1100":"environ 1100","Wales":"Galles","lifeSummary":"Mrs Cadafael Ynfyd ap Llywarch est née environ 1100, à Galles. Elle a eu au moins 1 fils avec Cadafael Ynfyd ap Llywarch."},"de":{"about 1100–":"um 1100–Verstorben","1100–Male":"1100–Verstorben","1130–Male":"1130–Verstorben","1100–Female":"1100